model_explanation: the word "only" in S1 places a restriction on what Sam gave Ellen—just bananas. But S2 says Sam gave Ellen grapes as well, which contradicts that restriction.
S1 says Sam only gave Mary apples, which means no other fruit was given to Mary. S2 confirms this by saying Sam didn’t give Mary oranges. So S2 logically follows from S1.
S1 restricts the gift to Tom as only bananas, while S2 claims Sam also gave Tom apples. This directly contradicts S1.
if Mary only got apples, it follows that she didn’t get grapes. S2 confirms this absence, making it entailed by S1.
if Sam only gave Mary oranges, that means Mary didn’t get any apples. S2 states that fact explicitly, so it is entailed by S1.
S1 says only Rob got apples. S2 brings in Mary, saying she also got apples. This doesn’t confirm or contradict S1 directly; it’s about someone else. So they are independent.
S1 says that only Rob got apples—excluding everyone else. S2 says Tom also got apples, which contradicts the restriction imposed by S1.
if Sam only gave Rob oranges, then by definition Sam didn’t give Rob bananas. S2 states that fact clearly, making it entailed by S1.
S1 says only Bill got grapes, while S2 introduces Rob getting grapes. This adds new information not covered by S1. The statements are independent, as shown.
S1 says Rob was only given grapes. S2 says Rob also got bananas, which contradicts S1’s restriction. This is the contradiction illustrated.
